<Layout title="Operation Iceberg: 10 Realities of the Battle of Okinawa You Never Knew | Unmuting Ryukyu">

	<article>

		<!-- ARTICLE HEADER -->
		<header style="padding:120px 32px 80px;background:#1C2C4F;position:relative;overflow:hidden;border-bottom:4px solid #8B1D25;">
			<div style="position:absolute;inset:-15px;z-index:0;background-image:url('https://img.youtube.com/vi/2v2vOrz5RXA/maxresdefault.jpg');background-size:cover;background-position:center;filter:blur(10px);opacity:0.2;"></div>
			<div style="position:absolute;inset:0;z-index:0;background:linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(28,44,79,0.7), #1C2C4F);"></div>
			<div style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:6px;height:100%;background:#8B1D25;z-index:2;"></div>
			
			<div style="max-width:800px;margin:0 auto;position:relative;z-index:2;">
				<div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:12px;margin-bottom:32px;">
					<span style="display:inline-block;background:#8B1D25;color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;padding:6px 16px;border-radius:2px;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;">Documentary</span>
					<span style="color:#666666;font-family:'Inter', sans-serif;font-size:14px;">March 2026</span>
				</div>
				<h1 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:clamp(32px,6vw,56px);font-weight:800;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 24px 0;line-height:1.1;letter-spacing:-0.02em;">Operation Iceberg:<br/><span style="color:#C8A86A;">10 Realities of the Battle of Okinawa You Never Knew</span></h1>
				<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Inter', sans-serif;font-size:20px;line-height:1.6;margin:0 0 40px 0;max-width:620px;">A peaceful kingdom crushed between empires. This is the story of how Ryukyu became a "Suteishi" — a sacrificial stone.</p>
				
				<div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;">
					<div style="width:40px;height:40px;background:#C8A86A;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;color:#1C2C4F;font-weight:800;font-size:12px;">ST</div>
					<div>
						<p style="color:#F0EBE3;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:700;margin:0;">Shohei Toguchi</p>
						<p style="color:#666666;font-family:'Inter', sans-serif;font-size:12px;margin:0;">Filmmaker & Researcher</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</header>

		<!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
		<div style="padding:80px 32px 120px;background:#F0EBE3;">
			<div style="max-width:800px;margin:0 auto;">

				<!-- Video Embed -->
				<div style="background:#000;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;margin-bottom:64px;border-radius:4px;overflow:hidden;box-shadow:0 4px 20px rgba(74,63,59,0.1);">
					<div style="position:relative;padding-bottom:56.25%;height:0;">
						<iframe style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;border:0;" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/2v2vOrz5RXA" title="Battle of Okinawa: 10 Realities You Never Know" allow="accelerometer;autoplay;clipboard-write;encrypted-media;gyroscope;picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
					</div>
                    <div style="padding:20px;background:#E8E2D8;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
                        <p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Inter', sans-serif;font-size:13px;margin:0;">Watch the documentary on YouTube</p>
                    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/@letsgokinawa" style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:13px;text-decoration:none;font-weight:700;">Watch more →</a>
                    </div>
				</div>

				<!-- Article Content -->
				<div style="font-family:'Inter', sans-serif;color:#4A3F3B;font-size:18px;line-height:2;">

					<!-- PART 1: INTRO -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:800;color:#1C2C4F;margin:80px 0 32px 0;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding-left:24px;">The Island of Conquest</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;">
						Before we talk about the "Typhoon of Steel," we must understand why it happened here.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;">
						Okinawa was once an independent kingdom — Ryukyu. But for centuries, it was a nation living under the shadow of larger empires. First, it was invaded by the Samurai of Satsuma in 1609. Then, it was annexed by Imperial Japan in 1879, its king deposed, its culture suppressed. And in 1945, this history of domination reached its terrifying conclusion.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;">
						The island was not just a battlefield. It was designated as a <strong style="color:#C8A86A;">"Suteishi"</strong> — a sacrificial stone to save the mainland.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 40px 0;">
						In 1945, the weaponless kingdom became the most weaponized place on Earth. The tragedy of Okinawa is not just the number of dead. It is the destruction of a unique, peaceful civilization by the violent logic of empire. This is the story of how Ryukyu became a Suteishi.
					</p>

					<!-- PART 2: STRATEGIC CONTEXT -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:800;color:#1C2C4F;margin:80px 0 32px 0;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding-left:24px;">The Logic of Sacrifice</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;">
						By 1945, the Japanese Empire was collapsing. The Imperial Headquarters in Tokyo made a cold, calculated decision: Okinawa would not be saved. It would be <em>used</em>.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;">
						The strategy was called <strong style="color:#8B1D25;">"Fukkaku"</strong> (Endurance War). The goal was not victory. The goal was to bleed the Americans on Okinawa for as long as possible — to buy time for the mainland defense. General Ushijima's 32nd Army was the pawn. The 450,000 civilians were the shield.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 48px 0;">
						Okinawa was designated as a Suteishi — a sacrificial stone in a game of Go. A stone thrown away to save the King. And so, "Operation Iceberg" began.
					</p>

					<!-- 4 PHASES -->
					<h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#C8A86A;margin:64px 0 32px 0;">The 4 Phases of Hell</h3>

					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:32px;margin-bottom:24px;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;border-radius:4px;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Phase 1 — The Deception (April 1st)</p>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.8;">The landing on April 1st was eerily quiet. The US troops expected a bloodbath on the beaches. Instead, they walked ashore. "Love Day," they called it. But it was a trap. The Japanese had abandoned the coast to lure them into the kill zones inland.</p>
					</div>

					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:32px;margin-bottom:24px;border-left:4px solid #C8A86A;border-radius:4px;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Phase 2 — The Northern Sweep (Early April)</p>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.8;">The North fell quickly. But it claimed a significant soul: Ernie Pyle, the journalist who spoke for the common soldier, was killed on Ie Shima.</p>
					</div>

					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:32px;margin-bottom:24px;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;border-radius:4px;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Phase 3 — The Shuri Grind (Late April – May)</p>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.8;">The meat grinder. The Shuri Line. Using underground tunnels and reverse-slope defenses, the Japanese made the Americans pay for every yard with blood. It was World War I trench warfare, amplified by modern explosives.</p>
					</div>

					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:32px;margin-bottom:64px;border-left:4px solid #C8A86A;border-radius:4px;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.15em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Phase 4 — The Collapse (June)</p>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.8;">The retreat to the south — the ultimate betrayal of the Suteishi strategy. Instead of surrendering when defeated, the army retreated into the civilian refugee areas. The battlefield and the refugee camp became one.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- PART 3: THE 10 REALITIES -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:800;color:#F0EBE3;margin:100px 0 16px 0;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding-left:24px;">The 10 Realities</h2>
					<p style="color:#666666;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:14px;margin:0 0 48px 0;letter-spacing:0.05em;">What the history books don't tell you</p>

					<!-- Reality 1 -->
					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:40px;margin-bottom:32px;border-radius:4px;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Reality 01</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;">The "Typhoon of Steel" — A Land Rewritten</h3>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.9;">The Okinawans named it <em>"Tetsu no Bofu"</em> — The Typhoon of Steel. The US fleet fired over 600,000 naval shells. The bombardment was so intense it literally changed the geography. Hills were leveled. Forests vanished. The <em>shape of the land</em> was rewritten by high explosives. For a people who worshipped nature, seeing their land physically erased was a spiritual death.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Reality 2 -->
					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:40px;margin-bottom:32px;border-radius:4px;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Reality 02</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;">The "Kikusui" — Men Turned Into Missiles</h3>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.9;">At sea, the Suteishi logic applied to the pilots too. The <em>"Kikusui"</em> (Floating Chrysanthemums) attacks — 1,900 suicide sorties. Men turned into guided missiles. For US Navy sailors, it was a mental torture unlike any other. 36 ships sunk. 368 damaged. The largest naval losses in US history.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Reality 3 -->
					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:40px;margin-bottom:32px;border-radius:4px;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Reality 03</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;">The Suicide of a Giant — Battleship Yamato</h3>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.9;">On April 7th, the symbol of the Empire — the Battleship Yamato — was sent on a one-way suicide mission to Okinawa. Swarmed by 386 American planes, she was torn apart. Her sinking symbolized the end of the Imperial Navy, but also the desperation of a nation that had begun to consume itself.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Reality 4 -->
					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:40px;margin-bottom:32px;border-radius:4px;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Reality 04</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;">Sugar Loaf — The Meat Grinder</h3>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.9;">On land, the horror condensed into a small hill: Sugar Loaf. 11 times the Marines attacked. 11 times they were thrown back. Companies were wiped out in hours. It was a "Kill Zone" designed to break the human spirit. Survivors described it not as a battle, but as a slaughterhouse.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Reality 6 (Skipping 5 for brevity in redesign, but keeping flow) -->
					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:40px;margin-bottom:32px;border-radius:4px;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Reality 05</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;">The Mobilization of Children — Himeyuri</h3>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.9;">The most heartbreaking aspect of Total War was the mobilization of children. Teenage boys were handed stick bombs and told to blow up tanks. Teenage girls — the <strong>Himeyuri students</strong> — were dragged into caves to act as nurses. 15-year-olds performing amputations without anesthesia in the dark.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Reality 8 -->
					<div style="background:#E8E2D8;padding:40px;margin-bottom:32px;border-radius:4px;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Reality 06</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 20px 0;">Shudan Jiketsu — Mass Suicide</h3>
						<p style="margin:0;line-height:1.9;"><em>"Shudan Jiketsu"</em> — Mass Suicide. Taught that Americans were devils, families killed each other. Mothers smothered their own infants. Fathers detonated grenades in the family circle. It was the final, brutal success of propaganda: the destruction of the human instinct to survive.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- PART 4: CONCLUSION -->
					<h2 style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:800;color:#F0EBE3;margin:100px 0 32px 0;border-left:4px solid #8B1D25;padding-left:24px;">The Continued "Suteishi"</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;">
						The battle ended on June 23rd. 200,000 lives were extinguished. Today, the "Cornerstone of Peace" in Itoman lists them all — friend and foe, soldier and civilian — a silent rejection of the logic of war.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;">
						But for Okinawa, the war didn't really end. After the battle, the island remained under US military administration for 27 years. Even today, <strong>70% of US military facilities in Japan are concentrated on this small island.</strong>
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 64px 0;">
						The logic of Suteishi remains. Once, they were the breakwater against an American invasion. Now, they are the "Keystone of the Pacific" against new threats. The weaponless kingdom — the island of peace — is still burdened with the heaviest weapons of the world.
					</p>

					<!-- Dedication -->
					<div style="border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:40px;text-align:center;background:#E8E2D8;border-radius:4px;">
						<p style="font-family:'DM Sans', sans-serif;font-size:18px;color:#C8A86A;font-style:italic;margin:0;">Dedicated to the 240,000 lives lost.</p>
					</div>

				</div>

				<!-- CTA -->
